        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">Estimated value. Word production of concrete amounts to 25 billion tonnes of which 10.6% are produced in EU (WBCSD 2009). The waste generation is estimated to be 15% (taken from the estimated value for gypsum, source: WRAP "International practice in plasterboard recycling: Canada", n.d). 1/3 of total waste is assumed to be concrete not reinforced, 1/3 concrete reinforced, and 1/3 concrete. Eurostat reports treatment methods for municipal waste for EU 27 in 2010 to be: 23% incineration; 37% landfilling; 25% recycling; 14% compost / digestion. The shares sent to landfill and recycling are divided to include sorting. It is assumed that half the product is sent directly to recycling and half goes through sorting; knowing that 40% of the waste sent to sorting is landfilled, while 60% is recycled the corresponding shares are calculated. References: Eurostat. Municipal waste generation &amp; treatment, by treatment method. Retrieved from: &lt;http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/waste/municipal-waste-generation-and-treatment-by-treatment-method&gt;, accessed 7th July 2016 WBCSD (2009) Recycling concrete. The Cement Sustainability Initiative. Retrieved from: http://www.wbcsdcement.org/index.php/en/publications, accessed 3 May 2016 WRAP(n.d.) International practice in plasterboard recycling: Canada. Retrieved from: http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Case%20study%20-%20Plasterboard%20recycling%20in%20Canada.pdf, accessed 3 May 2016</productionVolumeComment>
        <classification classificationId="ee3238ec-ca7a-4ddc-af1b-e7c35957b9b6">
          <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">By-product classification</classificationSystem>
          <classificationValue xml:lang="en">Waste</classificationValue>
        </classification>
